<subSubSection id="85EF16C9FFA07C6DFFD3F362FE052756" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="106" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CD4A4542FFA07C6DFFD3F362FE852534" blockId="1.[113,1089,619,1603]" lastBlockId="3.[113,1089,218,675]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="106" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis id="FF819950FFA07C6FFFD3F362FF072126" bold="true" box="[113,238,1323,1347]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Discussion.</emphasis>
The type locality of this species is 
<collectingCountry id="B5E205D2FFA07C6FFDF3F362FD5D2126" box="[593,692,1323,1347]" name="Germany" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Germany</collectingCountry>
, probably the environs of Württenberg (VON 
<bibRefCitation id="A96438B3FFA07C6FFF08F305FEC42106" author="ROSER C. VON" box="[170,301,1355,1379]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" pagination="49 - 64" refId="ref2989" refString="ROSER C. VON 1840: III. Beitrag zur Vaterlandkunde. Erster Nachtrag zu dem in Jahre 1834 bekannt gemachten Verzeichnisse in Wurttenberg vorkommenden zweiflugligen Insecten. Correspodensblatt der Koniglich Wurttenbergischen Landswirtschaftlichen Vereins (Stuttgart, Tubingen) 1 (1): 49 - 64." type="journal article" year="1840">ROSER 1840</bibRefCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="124EFBE0FFA07C6FFED2F302FE242106" box="[368,461,1355,1379]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">holotype</typeStatus>
designation is unclear and its depository is unknown. The original Latin description of 
<taxonomicName id="0AF53EC1FFA07C6FFE04F325FDD621E6" authority="Meigen, 1826" authorityName="von Roser" authorityYear="1840" box="[422,575,1388,1411]" class="Insecta" family="Scathophagidae" genus="Cordylura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">
<emphasis id="FF819950FFA07C6FFE04F325FDD621E6" box="[422,575,1388,1411]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">C. longicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very brief: ‘thorace cinereo, abdomine nigro, palpi albis; antennis longitudine capitis; pedibus flavis, posticis apice femorum et tibiarum fuscis’ [= thorax grey, abdomen black, palpi pale; antennae as long as head; legs yellow, tips of hind femora and tibiae darkened] (VON 
<bibRefCitation id="A96438B3FFA07C6FFD91F385FD5F2186" author="ROSER C. VON" box="[563,694,1483,1507]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" pagination="49 - 64" refId="ref2989" refString="ROSER C. VON 1840: III. Beitrag zur Vaterlandkunde. Erster Nachtrag zu dem in Jahre 1834 bekannt gemachten Verzeichnisse in Wurttenberg vorkommenden zweiflugligen Insecten. Correspodensblatt der Koniglich Wurttenbergischen Landswirtschaftlichen Vereins (Stuttgart, Tubingen) 1 (1): 49 - 64." type="journal article" year="1840">ROSER 1840</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="A96438B3FFA07C6FFD6AF385FC8F2186" author="BECKER T." box="[712,870,1483,1507]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" pagination="77 - 196" refId="ref2840" refString="BECKER T. 1894: Dipterologische Studien. I. Scatomyzidae. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift 39: 77 - 196." type="journal article" year="1894">BECKER (1894)</bibRefCitation>
somewhat extended the original description, e.g. by stating: ‘femoribus anticis intus setis nullis’ [= fore femora without short bristles on its interior side], fronte prominente antice flava, antennis nigris longis angustis, vibrissa unica [= frons prominent and anteriorly yellow, antennae black, long and narrow, only one vibrissa]. An important fact mentioned in the German part of the redescription is: ‘...das zweite Borstenglied bei Männchen verlängert’ [= second article of arista in male prolonged…]. It is evident from Becker’s text that he had both sexes at hand (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="A96438B3FFA27C6DFF3EF773FE892534" author="BECKER T." box="[156,352,313,338]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="77 - 196" refId="ref2840" refString="BECKER T. 1894: Dipterologische Studien. I. Scatomyzidae. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift 39: 77 - 196." type="journal article" year="1894">BECKER 1894: 115</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
